558
00:30:42,800 --> 00:30:47,280
which meant we needed
a very strong character
actor to play that part.

559
00:30:48,160 --> 00:30:50,640
NARRATOR: <i>Signing Guinness</i>
<i>was a major coup.</i>

560
00:30:50,720 --> 00:30:53,440
<i>But more casting would</i>
<i>be done in London,</i>

561
00:30:53,520 --> 00:30:56,000
<i>where </i>Star Wars
<i>would be principally produced.</i>

562
00:30:56,080 --> 00:30:59,120
<i>Unlike Lucas's home base</i>
<i>of Northern California,</i>

563
00:30:59,200 --> 00:31:02,360
<i>London provided</i>
<i>access to the kind</i>
<i>of massive soundstages</i>

564
00:31:02,480 --> 00:31:05,240
<i>needed for </i>Star Wars'
<i>ambitious sets.</i>

565
00:31:05,320 --> 00:31:09,480
<i>The location also gave Lucas</i>
<i>access to Britain's top</i>
<i>production talents.</i>

566
00:31:15,160 --> 00:31:19,640
<i>The character of Darth Vader</i>
<i>demanded someone of</i>
<i>commanding physical stature.</i>

567
00:31:21,040 --> 00:31:22,920
<i>To fill Vader's boots,</i>

568
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:26,320
<i>Lucas cast</i>
<i>champion bodybuilder</i>
<i>David Prowse,</i>

569
00:31:26,480 --> 00:31:29,920
<i>whose resume included roles</i>
<i>like Frankenstein's creature</i>

570
00:31:30,040 --> 00:31:32,720
<i>in Hammer's popular</i>
<i>horror movies.</i>

571
00:31:32,800 --> 00:31:35,760
<i>As Vader's evil accomplice</i>
<i>Governor Tarkin,</i>

572
00:31:35,880 --> 00:31:40,640
<i>another Hammer</i>
<i>alumnus was cast,</i>
<i>63-year-old Peter Cushing.</i>

573
00:31:40,720 --> 00:31:44,720
<i>Best known as the</i>
<i>methodical Professor Van</i>
<i>Helsing in </i>Dracula,

574
00:31:44,880 --> 00:31:46,680
<i>Cushing was</i>
<i>the perfect choice</i>

575
00:31:46,800 --> 00:31:49,440
<i>to portray the Death Star's</i>
<i>icy chief administrator.</i>

576
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:56,040
<i>For the part of</i>
<i>Chewbacca, Han Solo's</i>
<i>towering Wookiee co-pilot,</i>

577
00:31:56,120 --> 00:32:00,240
<i>Lucas and Kurtz</i>
<i>had to look outside</i>
<i>normal casting channels.</i>

578
00:32:00,320 --> 00:32:02,480
<i>But at seven feet,</i>
<i>three inches tall,</i>

579
00:32:02,560 --> 00:32:04,840
<i>it was no stretch</i>
<i>for Peter Mayhew,</i>

580
00:32:04,920 --> 00:32:08,440
<i>who had been working</i>
<i>as an orderly at</i>
<i>a Yorkshire hospital.</i>

581
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:12,040
I sat down
on one of the sofas

582
00:32:12,800 --> 00:32:14,520
waiting for George.

583
00:32:15,040 --> 00:32:17,040
Door opened,

584
00:32:17,360 --> 00:32:21,920
and George walked in
with Gary behind him.

585
00:32:22,480 --> 00:32:24,240
So, naturally, what did I do?

586
00:32:24,320 --> 00:32:25,680
I'm raised in England.

587
00:32:26,320 --> 00:32:29,880
Soon as someone
comes in through
the door, I stand up.

588
00:32:30,960 --> 00:32:33,440
George goes, "Hmm."

589
00:32:33,560 --> 00:32:35,960
Virtually turned
to Gary and said,

590
00:32:36,040 --> 00:32:38,040
"I think we've found him."

591
00:32:39,040 --> 00:32:41,160
NARRATOR: <i>Finding</i>
<i>the right performers</i>
<i>to portray robots</i>

592
00:32:41,240 --> 00:32:43,360
<i>was even more of a challenge.</i>

593
00:32:43,680 --> 00:32:47,840
<i>Production designers had</i>
<i>constructed an assortment</i>
<i>of robots and androids</i>

594
00:32:48,040 --> 00:32:50,920
<i>to populate the </i>Star Wars
<i>universe.</i>
(ROBOT BEEPS)

595
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:54,040
<i>But it would take living,</i>
<i>breathing actors</i>
<i>to give personality</i>

596
00:32:54,160 --> 00:32:58,640
<i>to the two main droids,</i>
<i>C3PO and R2D2.</i>

597
00:32:59,280 --> 00:33:00,880
<i>To operate R2,</i>

598
00:33:00,960 --> 00:33:03,560
<i>Lucas needed a performer</i>
<i>small in stature,</i>

599
00:33:03,640 --> 00:33:05,800
<i>but with a big imagination.</i>

600
00:33:06,040 --> 00:33:09,760
<i>Enter 3'5" stage comedian</i>
<i>Kenny Baker.</i>

601
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:12,560
KENNY BAKER:<i> They couldn't</i>
<i>find anyone that would</i>
<i>fit inside this robot</i>

602
00:33:12,640 --> 00:33:14,640
<i>to make it move,</i>

603
00:33:14,760 --> 00:33:17,240
and they couldn't use kids
'cause it was quite a heavy
machine, you know.

604
00:33:17,320 --> 00:33:19,200
It weighed about 80 pounds.

605
00:33:19,600 --> 00:33:23,440
<i>I'd had a lot of experience</i>
<i>inside costumes</i>

606
00:33:23,560 --> 00:33:27,200
<i>and inside cats and dogs</i>
<i>and goodness knows what else.</i>

607
00:33:27,280 --> 00:33:30,560
So when I got into
the robot, he said,
"Look happy."

608
00:33:30,640 --> 00:33:32,400
So I'd go...

609
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:37,280
Inside. Nobody could see
my expressions, obviously.

610
00:33:37,360 --> 00:33:42,000
But it just... You have to do
something to get the
feel of the thing.

611
00:33:43,800 --> 00:33:45,360
NARRATOR:
<i>Actor Anthony Daniels</i>

612
00:33:45,440 --> 00:33:48,680
<i>not only had the slender build</i>
<i>needed for C3PO,</i>

613
00:33:48,800 --> 00:33:50,800
<i>but training as a mime artist.</i>

614
00:33:50,920 --> 00:33:53,240
ANTHONY DANIELS:
<i>He'd been seeing people</i>
<i>every five minutes.</i>

615
00:33:53,320 --> 00:33:57,120
I was there for a while
and thinking, "Well, nearly
time to go, I guess."

616
00:33:57,200 --> 00:34:01,120
And then, kind of
over George's shoulder,
I saw a painting,

617
00:34:01,200 --> 00:34:03,080
<i>and the most extraordinary</i>
<i>thing happened.</i>

618
00:34:03,160 --> 00:34:06,840
<i>It just struck me,</i>
<i>because I kind of looked</i>
<i>at this face,</i>

619
00:34:06,920 --> 00:34:10,160
<i>and the face looked back</i>
<i>at me, and we had this</i>
<i>extraordinary eye contact.</i>

620
00:34:10,240 --> 00:34:13,280
He's looking right out of
the picture, and he seemed
to be saying,

621
00:34:13,600 --> 00:34:15,280
"Come. Come. Be with me."

622
00:34:15,360 --> 00:34:18,280
And the vulnerability
in his face

623
00:34:18,360 --> 00:34:20,080
made me want to help him.

624
00:34:20,200 --> 00:34:23,440
<i>Isn't that weird?</i>
<i>He just looks</i>
<i>utterly vulnerable.</i>

625
00:34:23,520 --> 00:34:27,640
<i>That painting completely</i>
<i>changed my attitude to</i>
<i>the whole project.</i>

626
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:31,080
Years later I was able to go
to Ralph McQuarrie and say,

627
00:34:31,160 --> 00:34:34,720
"You realize this is
all your fault."
(LAUGHS)

628
00:34:37,440 --> 00:34:40,480
NARRATOR: <i>In March 1976,</i>
<i>with casting completed,</i>

629
00:34:40,560 --> 00:34:44,440
<i>George Lucas and company</i>
<i>arrived in North Africa.</i>

630
00:34:46,480 --> 00:34:49,640
<i>It was a strange caravan</i>
<i>of British and</i>
<i>American filmmakers</i>

631
00:34:49,720 --> 00:34:54,000
<i>working in a French-speaking</i>
<i>nation on a script few</i>
<i>people believed in.</i>

632
00:34:55,320 --> 00:34:59,880
NORMAN REYNOLDS:<i> The</i>
<i>overriding thing for me,</i>
<i>really, at that stage was</i>

633
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:01,880
the amount of work
that we had to do,

634
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:05,120
the amount of stuff
there was to achieve,

635
00:35:05,640 --> 00:35:08,680
<i>and we had grave doubts</i>
<i>about getting it done in time.</i>

636
00:35:12,960 --> 00:35:15,960
NARRATOR:
<i>But the trial by fire</i>
<i>had yet to begin.</i>

637
00:35:16,040 --> 00:35:18,600
<i>It was now up to Lucas</i>
<i>to make his movie.</i>

638
00:35:19,560 --> 00:35:21,400
<i>Just one day into filming,</i>

639
00:35:21,480 --> 00:35:25,720
<i>the Sahara was pelted with</i>
<i>its first major rainfall</i>
<i>in 50 years.</i>

640
00:35:25,920 --> 00:35:29,080
ROBERT WATTS:<i> We were</i>
<i>going out there to shoot</i>
<i>on the salt flat.</i>

641
00:35:29,160 --> 00:35:32,200
I came out in the morning
and the rain was going
horizontally down the street.

642
00:35:32,280 --> 00:35:33,600
This way.

643
00:35:33,720 --> 00:35:35,600
I thought, "My God".

644
00:35:35,720 --> 00:35:38,600
I just called a rest day
on the crew, told them
all to go back to bed,

645
00:35:38,680 --> 00:35:41,280
because there was no way
we were gonna shoot on that.

646
00:35:45,200 --> 00:35:48,000
LUCAS:<i> The first two weeks of</i>
<i>shooting we'd run into a lot</i>
<i>of weather problems.</i>

647
00:35:48,080 --> 00:35:51,120
<i>The sets had blown down,</i>
<i>I didn't get everything shot.</i>

648
00:35:51,320 --> 00:35:52,880
It was a disaster.

649
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:55,120
At that point
I was pretty
depressed, saying,

650
00:35:55,200 --> 00:35:58,240
"Boy, I've gotten myself in
way over my head.

651
00:35:58,320 --> 00:35:59,880
"I don't know
what I'm gonna do."

652
00:36:00,120 --> 00:36:02,720
You must do what you feel
is right, of course.

653
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:08,360
NARRATOR: <i>With temperatures</i>
<i>topping 100 degrees</i>
<i>by mid-morning,</i>

654
00:36:08,480 --> 00:36:10,840
<i>Tunisia was anything</i>
<i>but fun in the sun.</i>

655
00:36:10,920 --> 00:36:12,200
WOMAN:<i> Luke! Luke!</i>

656
00:36:12,280 --> 00:36:14,560
<i>Baking for hours</i>
<i>in heavy costume,</i>

657
00:36:14,640 --> 00:36:17,440
<i>even the film's</i>
<i>stunt coordinator,</i>
<i>Peter Diamond,</i>

658
00:36:17,520 --> 00:36:20,040
<i>found the conditions</i>
<i>physically exhausting.</i>

659
00:36:20,160 --> 00:36:24,240
PETER DIAMOND:<i> I was the only</i>
<i>stunt person on the</i>
<i>picture in Tunisia.</i>

660
00:36:24,360 --> 00:36:27,240
<i>I became a Tusken Raider,</i>
<i>or a Sandperson.</i>

661
00:36:29,080 --> 00:36:32,560
I'm not a sun merchant.
I don't like the sun.
I just burn.

662
00:36:33,400 --> 00:36:35,200
<i>So I just died</i>
<i>with the heat of it.</i>

663
00:36:35,280 --> 00:36:37,480
<i>I couldn't stand it anymore,</i>
<i>it was so hot.</i>

664
00:36:37,560 --> 00:36:41,560
<i>There were so many problems.</i>
<i>It just was not</i>
<i>a good location.</i>

665
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:43,680
We seem to be made to suffer.

666
00:36:43,760 --> 00:36:45,200
It's our lot in life.

667
00:36:45,280 --> 00:36:48,360
C3PO was finally

668
00:36:48,440 --> 00:36:51,680
<i>put together for the very</i>
<i>first time</i>

669
00:36:51,760 --> 00:36:54,160
<i>the day before</i>
<i>we started shooting.</i>

670
00:36:54,960 --> 00:36:57,960
<i>R2D2 didn't really function</i>
<i>that well.</i>

671
00:36:58,040 --> 00:37:00,240
<i>He could run along</i>
<i>in the three-legged position,</i>

672
00:37:00,400 --> 00:37:03,280
<i>but he couldn't turn his head</i>
<i>at the same time.</i>

673
00:37:03,720 --> 00:37:05,960
BAKER:<i> There were</i>
<i>wires everywhere.</i>

674
00:37:06,040 --> 00:37:08,840
<i>The head was on a track</i>
<i>of ball bearings.</i>

675
00:37:08,920 --> 00:37:10,720
<i>I used to grab whatever</i>
<i>I could grab ahold of</i>

676
00:37:10,800 --> 00:37:13,080
<i>and turn it that way</i>
<i>and that way.</i>

677
00:37:13,160 --> 00:37:14,720
Not very far.

678
00:37:15,520 --> 00:37:19,040
Because if I went too far the
wires would go around my neck.

679
00:37:19,120 --> 00:37:21,840
<i>Then they'd say, "Cut!</i>
<i>All right, break for lunch."</i>

680
00:37:22,520 --> 00:37:24,840
<i>And everybody'd just walk away</i>
<i>and leave me.</i>

681
00:37:24,920 --> 00:37:27,600
<i>Then they'd remember</i>
<i>me eventually.</i>

682
00:37:28,160 --> 00:37:29,800
That happened many times.

683
00:37:30,400 --> 00:37:32,840
DANIELS:<i> It was bad enough</i>
<i>putting on the costume</i>
<i>for the first time,</i>

684
00:37:32,920 --> 00:37:36,200
<i>and within two paces</i>
<i>the left leg had</i>
<i>shattered down</i>

685
00:37:36,280 --> 00:37:39,200
<i>onto the plastic</i>
<i>of the left foot</i>

686
00:37:39,280 --> 00:37:42,080
<i>and was gently,</i>
<i>but forcibly and persistently,</i>

687
00:37:42,160 --> 00:37:45,120
knifing it into the...
(LAUGHING)

688
00:37:45,240 --> 00:37:48,200
The soft part of my foot.

689
00:37:48,280 --> 00:37:52,000
<i>So we took it off and I limped</i>
<i>to the set with one foot.</i>

690
00:37:52,080 --> 00:37:56,320
It was then I began to panic
about the days to come.

691
00:37:59,440 --> 00:38:03,280
NARRATOR:<i> As the actors</i>
<i>and crew began to grumble</i>
<i>about the adverse conditions,</i>

692
00:38:03,360 --> 00:38:07,040
<i>it was Sir Alec Guinness who</i>
<i>served as a role model</i>
<i>of professionalism.</i>

693
00:38:08,040 --> 00:38:11,440
FORD: <i>It was, for me,</i>
<i>fascinating to watch</i>
<i>Alec Guinness.</i>

694
00:38:11,520 --> 00:38:14,120
He was always prepared,
always professional,

695
00:38:14,200 --> 00:38:16,320
always very kind
to the other actors.

696
00:38:16,680 --> 00:38:20,160
<i>He had a very clear head</i>
<i>about how to serve the story.</i>

697
00:38:20,680 --> 00:38:24,440
HAMILL: <i>He was the person</i>
<i>who sort of brought</i>
<i>it some legitimacy.</i>

698
00:38:24,680 --> 00:38:26,720
<i>I asked him why he</i>
<i>wanted to do it.</i>

699
00:38:26,800 --> 00:38:29,720
He loved the idea of playing
a mentor or a wizard

700
00:38:30,080 --> 00:38:31,720
<i>in a morality play</i>

701
00:38:31,800 --> 00:38:34,280
<i>where good and evil</i>
<i>are so clearly defined.</i>

702
00:38:35,040 --> 00:38:36,320
MAN: Action!

703
00:38:38,960 --> 00:38:42,320
How long have you had
these droids?
Three or four seasons.

704
00:38:42,640 --> 00:38:44,960
They're up for sale
if you want them.

705
00:38:45,080 --> 00:38:46,960
Let me see
your identification.

706
00:38:47,080 --> 00:38:49,320
You don't need to see
his identification.

707
00:38:49,400 --> 00:38:51,320
GUARD: I don't need to see
your identification.

708
00:38:51,600 --> 00:38:53,920
These aren't the droids
you're looking for.

709
00:38:54,080 --> 00:38:55,960
GUARD:
These aren't the droids
we're looking for.

710
00:38:56,080 --> 00:38:57,600
He can go about
his business.

711
00:38:58,400 --> 00:39:00,280
GUARD: You can go
about your business.

712
00:39:00,600 --> 00:39:01,920
Move along.

713
00:39:06,320 --> 00:39:07,600
NARRATOR:<i> Lucas, meanwhile,</i>

714
00:39:07,680 --> 00:39:09,880
<i>was up to his neck in</i>
<i>malfunctioning props,</i>

715
00:39:10,400 --> 00:39:14,000
<i>electronic breakdowns,</i>
<i>and other production woes.</i>

716
00:39:15,560 --> 00:39:18,960
Star Wars <i>was already</i>
<i>struggling to stay</i>
<i>on schedule.</i>

717
00:39:19,720 --> 00:39:23,080
<i>The only silver lining</i>
<i>was that after Tunisia</i>

718
00:39:23,160 --> 00:39:26,160
<i>the production would be</i>
<i>moving to a more</i>
<i>controlled environment,</i>

719
00:39:26,240 --> 00:39:28,560
<i>Elstree Studios</i>
<i>outside London.</i>

720
00:39:30,240 --> 00:39:33,480
<i>The stages at Elstree</i>
<i>were among the largest</i>
<i>in the world,</i>

721
00:39:33,600 --> 00:39:36,960
<i>and the sets,</i>
<i>now finished after</i>
<i>months of construction,</i>

722
00:39:37,040 --> 00:39:38,640
<i>were just as impressive.</i>

723
00:39:38,720 --> 00:39:42,840
<i>And for the first time,</i>
<i>the entire </i>Star Wars
<i>cast was together.</i>

724
00:39:43,800 --> 00:39:46,320
HAMILL: <i>That was almost like</i>
<i>a whole separate movie.</i>

725
00:39:46,400 --> 00:39:48,760
It was like
getting a whole,
fresh start.

726
00:39:48,840 --> 00:39:50,680
It was all new, really.

727
00:39:51,680 --> 00:39:53,560
FISHER: <i>We were all</i>
<i>very different ages.</i>

728
00:39:53,840 --> 00:39:57,080
I was 19, Harrison was 33.

729
00:39:57,160 --> 00:39:59,840
He was sort of
the big man on campus.

730
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:04,280
<i>Meeting him, you sort of felt,</i>
<i>"Well, he'll be a movie star."</i>

731
00:40:05,120 --> 00:40:08,400
NARRATOR: <i>Costumes, makeup,</i>
<i>robots, and aliens</i>

732
00:40:08,480 --> 00:40:10,280
<i>were all ready to go.</i>

733
00:40:11,080 --> 00:40:12,640
MAYHEW:<i> I put that mask on</i>

734
00:40:12,720 --> 00:40:16,840
and Chewie transformed me.

735
00:40:16,920 --> 00:40:19,720
I transformed.
The attitude was different.

736
00:40:20,120 --> 00:40:23,040
<i>The walk was different.</i>
<i>Chewie turned on.</i>

737
00:40:23,640 --> 00:40:26,840
<i>Do the scenes, come back,</i>
<i>take the mask off,</i>

738
00:40:27,560 --> 00:40:28,880
<i>Peter was back.</i>

739
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:31,560
MAN: Action.

740
00:40:31,760 --> 00:40:33,320
That old man's mad.

741
00:40:34,280 --> 00:40:37,520
You said it, Chewie.
Boy, where did you
dig up that old fossil?

742
00:40:38,440 --> 00:40:41,760
Ben is a great man.
Yeah, great at getting
us into trouble.

743
00:40:41,840 --> 00:40:43,920
I didn't hear you
give any ideas.

744
00:40:44,280 --> 00:40:45,600
MAN: Okay, cut.

745
00:40:49,520 --> 00:40:51,440
NARRATOR: <i>But working</i>
<i>at Elstree Studios</i>

746
00:40:51,560 --> 00:40:54,320
<i>didn't mean the production</i>
<i>was free from problems</i>

747
