01:00:35,520 --> 01:00:37,560
We were going
on the front lines here,

1138
01:00:37,640 --> 01:00:40,640
and that gave us also kind of
a feeling of being special

1139
01:00:41,200 --> 01:00:45,160
<i>and fighting this great</i>
<i>battle to get this thing</i>
<i>done, whatever it is.</i>

1140
01:00:52,440 --> 01:00:54,600
NARRATOR: <i>To help inspire</i>
<i>the effects team at ILM,</i>

1141
01:00:54,880 --> 01:00:58,560
<i>Lucas had spliced</i>
<i>together aerial dogfights</i>
<i>from old war movies.</i>

1142
01:00:58,720 --> 01:01:02,360
That would be like the first
animatic, which you do
in the computer now,

1143
01:01:02,440 --> 01:01:06,440
<i>and we matched frame to frame</i>
<i>and did the action on</i>
<i>that as close as we could.</i>

1144
01:01:08,920 --> 01:01:10,400
Ha ha!

1145
01:01:10,520 --> 01:01:12,480
RALSTON:<i> And it</i>
<i>was hugely helpful.</i>

1146
01:01:14,080 --> 01:01:17,360
LUKE: I got him!
Great, kid!
Don't get cocky.

1147
01:01:17,800 --> 01:01:21,720
To describe
that abstract world
of a battle is impossible.

1148
01:01:21,800 --> 01:01:23,600
Storyboards don't do it,
as far as the pacing,

1149
01:01:23,680 --> 01:01:25,440
<i>the rhythms that he needed.</i>

1150
01:01:29,120 --> 01:01:30,240
Thanks, Wedge.

1151
01:01:30,320 --> 01:01:31,320
That was a great thing.

1152
01:01:41,160 --> 01:01:45,000
NARRATOR:<i> As fall</i>
<i>turned to winter,</i> Star Wars
<i>finally started to take shape.</i>

1153
01:01:45,080 --> 01:01:46,280
That's it! We did it!

1154
01:01:46,360 --> 01:01:47,520
We did it!

1155
01:01:48,800 --> 01:01:51,440
NARRATOR: <i>Working from</i>
<i>the raw production tracks,</i>

1156
01:01:52,520 --> 01:01:54,000
<i>sound designer Ben Burtt</i>

1157
01:01:54,080 --> 01:01:56,240
<i>would add a critical</i>
<i>new layer to the film.</i>

1158
01:01:57,440 --> 01:01:59,880
<i>Burtt had spent a year</i>
<i>building a catalog of sounds</i>

1159
01:01:59,960 --> 01:02:02,080
<i>for things that didn't exist</i>
<i>in our galaxy.</i>

1160
01:02:02,440 --> 01:02:05,880
(LASER BLASTING)

1161
01:02:05,960 --> 01:02:09,560
George introduced the idea
of what he called an
"organic sound track."

1162
01:02:10,080 --> 01:02:13,800
<i>George thought that Chewbacca</i>
<i>might be made up</i>

1163
01:02:13,920 --> 01:02:16,880
<i>from recordings of dogs</i>
<i>or maybe even bears.</i>

1164
01:02:17,120 --> 01:02:21,920
In addition, I recorded some
lions and tigers and even
some walruses.

1165
01:02:22,120 --> 01:02:23,760
(GROWLING)

1166
01:02:24,040 --> 01:02:26,360
I would begin
editing them together

1167
01:02:26,440 --> 01:02:29,080
and making little phrases
out of the noises.

1168
01:02:29,160 --> 01:02:31,200
I would take the recordings
and edit the best pieces.

1169
01:02:31,280 --> 01:02:34,280
(ROARING)
Argh!

1170
01:02:34,400 --> 01:02:36,600
You know, the bear might make
a sound that sounded angry.

1171
01:02:36,720 --> 01:02:38,400
Grr!

1172
01:02:38,520 --> 01:02:40,040
Or they might make
a sound that was cute

1173
01:02:40,120 --> 01:02:42,040
(GROWLING)

1174
01:02:42,520 --> 01:02:44,080
Argh.

1175
01:02:44,320 --> 01:02:47,840
Or a sound that sounded like
a sentence, a "wah-wah-wah
kind of a sound.

1176
01:02:47,920 --> 01:02:50,000
Argh, argh, argh!

1177
01:02:50,200 --> 01:02:51,760
You said it, Chewie.

1178
01:02:52,120 --> 01:02:55,600
The voice of R2 turned
out to be the most
difficult problem to solve

1179
01:02:55,680 --> 01:02:57,560
in the sound design
of the first movie

1180
01:02:58,600 --> 01:03:01,760
<i>because R2 had to act</i>
<i>alongside of the other actors.</i>

1181
01:03:01,880 --> 01:03:04,080
<i>And the script only said</i>

1182
01:03:04,160 --> 01:03:07,320
<i>that R2 made a sound,</i>
<i>or maybe R2 beeped.</i>

1183
01:03:08,000 --> 01:03:10,960
I had a small electronic
synthesizer,

1184
01:03:11,040 --> 01:03:14,280
<i>and I did some patches</i>
<i>with it and made up</i>
<i>some electronic sounds.</i>

1185
01:03:14,360 --> 01:03:16,240
<i>But that didn't sound alive.</i>

1186
01:03:16,320 --> 01:03:18,920
<i>At one point we talked</i>
<i>about R2's personality,</i>

1187
01:03:19,000 --> 01:03:23,200
and we felt he was developing
kind of as a toddler.

1188
01:03:23,280 --> 01:03:24,760
(BEEPING)

1189
01:03:24,840 --> 01:03:27,000
<i>So I did a lot</i>
<i>of baby recordings,</i>

1190
01:03:27,080 --> 01:03:30,560
<i>and eventually we found</i>
<i>that in the discussion</i>
<i>of R2's voice,</i>

1191
01:03:30,640 --> 01:03:32,560
<i>we were making</i>
<i>the sounds ourselves.</i>

1192
01:03:32,640 --> 01:03:34,400
(WHISTLES ROBOTICALLY)

1193
01:03:34,480 --> 01:03:37,920
A few experiments led to the
combination of using my voice

1194
01:03:38,000 --> 01:03:41,080
doing baby talk
beeps and "boops"...

1195
01:03:41,240 --> 01:03:43,000
(BEEPS)

1196
01:03:43,160 --> 01:03:44,840
...with the
electronic synthesizer.

1197
01:03:44,920 --> 01:03:48,880
So, R2 is sort
of 50% machine
and 50% organic,

1198
01:03:49,400 --> 01:03:52,160
<i>coming out of, you know,</i>
<i>the performance of a person.</i>

1199
01:03:54,480 --> 01:03:57,440
<i>The breathing for Vader</i>
<i>was recorded</i>

1200
01:03:57,520 --> 01:04:00,600
<i>by putting a little</i>
<i>tiny microphone down inside</i>

1201
01:04:00,680 --> 01:04:04,320
<i>a regulator on a scuba tank.</i>
(BREATHING MECHANICALLY)

1202
01:04:04,400 --> 01:04:09,200
I breathed through the mask
itself, and it breathed
in and out,

1203
01:04:09,280 --> 01:04:12,760
and out of that came the
various, you know, paces of
Vader breathing.

1204
01:04:12,840 --> 01:04:14,400
(BREATHING MECHANICALLY)

1205
01:04:14,880 --> 01:04:16,440
<i>And that sound worked out</i>
<i>pretty successfully.</i>

1206
01:04:21,120 --> 01:04:23,160
NARRATOR: <i>Finding the right</i>
<i>voice for Darth Vader</i>

1207
01:04:23,280 --> 01:04:24,880
<i>was another challenge.</i>

1208
01:04:25,440 --> 01:04:27,280
MAN: And action!

1209
01:04:27,360 --> 01:04:28,800
NARRATOR:<i> Lucas had</i>
<i>never intended to use</i>

1210
01:04:28,880 --> 01:04:31,400
<i>the onset vocal performance</i>
<i>of David Prowse.</i>

1211
01:04:32,640 --> 01:04:35,000
(MUFFLED BRITISH ACCENT)
Start tearing this ship
apart, piece by piece,

1212
01:04:35,080 --> 01:04:36,480
until you find those tapes!

1213
01:04:36,600 --> 01:04:39,240
Find the passengers
of this vessel!
I want them alive!

1214
01:04:39,600 --> 01:04:42,080
RALSTON: <i>I can still hear</i>
<i>David Prowse's accent</i>

1215
01:04:42,320 --> 01:04:44,640
in the Darth Vader
mask muffled,

1216
01:04:44,720 --> 01:04:46,120
'cause he would do
the real dialogue,

1217
01:04:46,240 --> 01:04:48,360
<i>in trying to curse</i>
<i>Carrie Fisher or something.</i>

1218
01:04:48,760 --> 01:04:50,480
I don't know what
you're talking about.

1219
01:04:50,560 --> 01:04:52,760
I'm a member of the
Imperial Senate on
a diplomatic mission

1220
01:04:52,840 --> 01:04:56,840
You are part of the Rebel
Alliance and a traitor.
Take her away!

1221
01:04:57,200 --> 01:04:59,640
It was hilarious
and terrifying
at the same time,

1222
01:04:59,720 --> 01:05:01,560
'cause we didn't know
what Darth sounded like.

1223
01:05:01,640 --> 01:05:04,320
That was the first time
we heard him. We were like,
"Is that it?

1224
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:07,280
"Is he gonna be some
Scottish guy,
or what is this?"

1225
01:05:08,080 --> 01:05:10,200
NARRATOR: <i>Prowse's voice</i>
<i>would later be replaced</i>

1226
01:05:10,280 --> 01:05:12,360
<i>with a more</i>
<i>menacing performance</i>
MAN: Cut it.

1227
01:05:12,440 --> 01:05:17,520
<i>Provided by classically</i>
<i>trained stage and film</i>
<i>actor James Earl Jones.</i>

1228
01:05:17,880 --> 01:05:20,360
JAMES EARL JONES:
<i>George had hired David Prowse,</i>

1229
01:05:20,560 --> 01:05:23,760
but he said he wanted
a so-called "darker" voice.

1230
01:05:24,160 --> 01:05:28,440
Not in terms of ethnic,
but in terms of timbre.

1231
01:05:29,280 --> 01:05:31,920
And the rumor is that
he thought of Orson Welles,

1232
01:05:33,200 --> 01:05:37,440
and then probably thought
that Orson might be
too recognizable.

1233
01:05:38,200 --> 01:05:41,680
So what he ends up
is picking a voice that
was born in Mississippi,

1234
01:05:41,760 --> 01:05:44,120
raised in Michigan,
and was a stutterer.

1235
01:05:45,480 --> 01:05:47,720
And, uh, that happened
to be my voice.

1236
01:05:47,920 --> 01:05:50,520
I want to know what happened
to the plans they sent you.

1237
01:05:50,880 --> 01:05:52,800
I don't know what
you're talking about.

1238
01:05:52,920 --> 01:05:54,640
I'm a member
of the Imperial Senate

1239
01:05:54,720 --> 01:05:56,200
on a diplomatic
mission to Alderaan.

1240
01:05:56,280 --> 01:05:59,200
You are part of the Rebel
Alliance and a traitor.

1241
01:05:59,440 --> 01:06:00,880
Take her away!

1242
01:06:01,280 --> 01:06:03,200
C3PO's voice struck us all
as, you know,

1243
01:06:03,280 --> 01:06:05,800
"Well, we've got to do
something about that."

1244
01:06:05,880 --> 01:06:07,200
Thirty-four,
take three.

1245
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:10,760
DANIELS: (MUFFLED) We seem
to be made to suffer.
It's our lot in life.

1246
01:06:10,840 --> 01:06:12,960
It was mentioned
a number of times

1247
01:06:13,040 --> 01:06:15,400
that C3PO might sound
like a used car salesman.

1248
01:06:15,600 --> 01:06:17,800
<i>Not the English butler type.</i>

1249
01:06:17,920 --> 01:06:20,400
(MUFFLED) I'm sorry, sir.
I must have fallen over.

1250
01:06:20,480 --> 01:06:22,400
I just came up
with this voice, um,

1251
01:06:22,480 --> 01:06:26,400
of an over-the-top
British butler.

1252
01:06:26,480 --> 01:06:29,960
Um, British because
that would be my natural
mode of thinking.

1253
01:06:30,040 --> 01:06:33,560
A butler because that was
his role in life.

1254
01:06:33,680 --> 01:06:36,560
Nervous because that
was his feeling in life.

1255
01:06:36,760 --> 01:06:39,720
And it came as, "C3PO,
human-cyborg relations."

1256
01:06:40,440 --> 01:06:42,200
This is my counterpart R2D2.

1257
01:06:42,680 --> 01:06:43,880
Hello.

1258
01:06:43,960 --> 01:06:44,960
(BEEPS THREE TIMES)

1259
01:06:45,040 --> 01:06:46,960
A few people
were brought in to record,

1260
01:06:47,040 --> 01:06:49,760
and an attempt was made
to see how 3PO would be

1261
01:06:49,840 --> 01:06:51,760
with different
kinds of voices.

1262
01:06:51,840 --> 01:06:55,480
I believe 30 actors came in
and some really quite
impressive names.

1263
01:06:55,600 --> 01:06:59,120
Stan Freberg
and a few others
were auditioned.

1264
01:06:59,200 --> 01:07:02,440
Apparently, one of them
was a major cartoon actor,

1265
01:07:02,520 --> 01:07:05,520
a man of literally
a thousand voices,
who eventually said,

1266
01:07:05,600 --> 01:07:09,040
"You know something,
George, Tony's voice is
pretty good for the character.

1267
01:07:09,120 --> 01:07:11,040
"Why don't you
just use his voice?"

1268
01:07:11,480 --> 01:07:14,040
And eventually the discussion
just quieted down,

1269
01:07:14,120 --> 01:07:16,200
<i>and it was</i>
<i>an excellent performance.</i>

1270
01:07:16,280 --> 01:07:18,440
<i>It synchronized with</i>
<i>his body motions.</i>

1271
01:07:18,520 --> 01:07:20,840
<i>It was a total character</i>
<i>which he created.</i>

1272
01:07:20,920 --> 01:07:22,840
<i>His track was</i>
<i>left in the movie.</i>

1273
01:07:23,440 --> 01:07:25,800
Hey! We don't serve
their kind here.

1274
01:07:25,960 --> 01:07:27,040
What?

1275
01:07:27,120 --> 01:07:29,200
Your droids,
they'll have to
wait outside.

1276
01:07:29,280 --> 01:07:30,320
We don't want them here.

1277
01:07:30,400 --> 01:07:32,760
Why don't you wait
out by the speeder?
We don't want any trouble.

1278
01:07:32,840 --> 01:07:34,040
I heartily agree
with you, sir.

1279
01:07:37,720 --> 01:07:40,680
428, take seven. Action!

1280
01:07:41,440 --> 01:07:43,800
Here we go.
Cutting the
sublight engines.

1281
01:07:46,280 --> 01:07:47,720
What the...

1282
01:07:47,800 --> 01:07:50,720
NARRATOR: <i>At long last,</i>
<i>the editing, sound,</i>

1283
01:07:50,800 --> 01:07:52,720
<i>and visual effects</i>
<i>were taking shape.</i>

1284
01:07:55,240 --> 01:07:59,040
<i>But a private screening of</i>
<i>the film for Lucas's</i>
<i>closest friends</i>

1285
01:07:59,120 --> 01:08:01,040
<i>didn't do much</i>
<i>to bolster his confidence.</i>

1286
01:08:01,120 --> 01:08:02,120
No!

1287
01:08:02,440 --> 01:08:04,480
It was an early stage.

1288
01:08:04,600 --> 01:08:07,320
You know, sort of
a second or third cut.

1289
01:08:07,840 --> 01:08:10,840
<i>I had a couple of my friends</i>
<i>come up to see it.</i>

1290
01:08:10,920 --> 01:08:13,000
<i>Brian De Palma was in town.</i>
<i>Steven came.</i>

1291
01:08:13,080 --> 01:08:15,440
<i>Some other friends</i>
<i>came to see it.</i>

1292
01:08:15,520 --> 01:08:17,760
SPIELBERG:<i> The human</i>
<i>characters and the sets</i>
<i>were there,</i>

1293
01:08:17,840 --> 01:08:20,520
but, of course,
all the spectacular...

1294
01:08:20,600 --> 01:08:23,680
You know,
the Death Star fight

1295
01:08:23,760 --> 01:08:25,200
and the battle
inside the trench,

1296
01:08:25,280 --> 01:08:29,040
and all that was just, um,
not even there to be seen.

1297
01:08:32,280 --> 01:08:34,920
So, the reaction
was not a good one.
I loved the movie.

1298
01:08:35,000 --> 01:08:37,560
I was probably one of the only
people in the audience that
liked the movie.

1299
01:08:37,640 --> 01:08:41,840
LUCAS:<i> All my friends were</i>
<i>very honest. "I don't get it.</i>
<i>What are you doing here?"</i>

1300
01:08:41,920 --> 01:08:44,120
So that was basically
the tenor of the whole thing.

1301
01:08:44,200 --> 01:08:46,040
On the other hand,
the studio,

1302
01:08:46,120 --> 01:08:49,560
when Laddie and his
little group saw the film,
they loved it.

1303
01:08:50,080 --> 01:08:52,400
It was the first time
I've actually shown
a film, um,

1304
01:08:52,520 --> 01:08:55,080
and one of the executives
even cried at the screening.

1305
01:08:55,160 --> 01:08:56,840
<i>It was, like,</i>
<i>very emotional for him.</i>

1306
01:08:58,560 --> 01:09:02,600
WIGAN:<i> I sat my family round</i>
<i>the kitchen table in my house,</i>

1307
01:09:02,800 --> 01:09:06,760
and I said, "The most
extraordinary day of my
life has just taken place.

1308
01:09:06,840 --> 01:09:08,400
"I want you to
remember this day.

1309
01:09:08,480 --> 01:09:12,800
"Because this is what I never
dreamed or maybe I dreamed

1310
01:09:12,880 --> 01:09:15,440
"but I never thought I would
have a day's experience

1311
01:09:15,520 --> 01:09:17,960
"like the day I've had today
in seeing this film."

1312
01:09:18,160 --> 01:09:20,720
You know, I couldn't even
believe it, 'cause I'm used
to studios...

1313
01:09:20,800 --> 01:09:23,520
At that point I was used to
studio chiefs saying,
"This is terrible.

1314
01:09:23,600 --> 01:09:26,080
"You shouldn't show this
to an audience. Embarrassing."

1315
01:09:26,680 --> 01:09:29,360
<i>So, for me it was</i>
<i>a very rewarding thing</i>

1316
01:09:29,440 --> 01:09:31,720
<i>to show it to people,</i>
<i>even though it was</i>
<i>in bad shape.</i>

1317
01:09:31,800 --> 01:09:35,840
NARRATOR:<i> It didn't help that</i>
<i>one critical element in</i>
Star Wars <i>was still missing.</i>

1318
01:09:36,480 --> 01:09:37,760
There's no lock.

1319
01:09:38,840 --> 01:09:40,440
<i>The musical score.</i>

1320
01:09:41,520 --> 01:09:42,840
That oughta hold
them for a while.

1321
01:09:42,920 --> 01:09:44,240
Quick! We've got
to get across.

1322
01:09:44,360 --> 01:09:46,000
Find the controls
that extend the bridge.

1323
01:09:46,160 --> 01:09:47,640
LUKE: I think I just
blasted it.

1324
01:09:47,760 --> 01:09:49,480
They're coming
through!

1325
01:09:50,560 --> 01:09:52,160
I remember bugging
George, like,

1326
01:09:52,240 --> 01:09:55,280
"When can we hear the score?
When can we hear the score?"

1327
01:09:55,720 --> 01:09:58,280
NARRATOR:<i> Fortunately,</i>
<i>Lucas was able to recruit</i>

1328
01:09:58,360 --> 01:10:02,080
<i>one of the industry's most</i>
<i>accomplished composers,</i>
<i>John Williams.</i>

1329
01:10:02,840 --> 01:10:04,920
<i>Williams had recently</i>
<i>won an Oscar</i>

1330
01:10:05,000 --> 01:10:07,200
<i>for Steven Spielberg's </i>Jaws,

1331
01:10:07,280 --> 01:10:11,320
<i>and his resume included</i>
<i>countless film and</i>
<i>television scores,</i>

1332
01:10:11,720 --> 01:10:15,280
<i>including music for</i>
<i>the original</i> Lost in Space
<i>television series.</i>

1333
01:10:17,520 --> 01:10:20,480
JOHN WILLIAMS:
<i>I do remember George</i>
<i>talking about the fact</i>

1334
01:10:20,600 --> 01:10:22,760
<i>that what we were</i>
<i>going to see</i>
<i>in the film</i>

1335
01:10:22,840 --> 01:10:25,560
represents worlds
that we hadn't seen,

1336
01:10:26,040 --> 01:10:29,240
but that the music should
give us some kind of
an emotional anchor.

1337
01:10:29,760 --> 01:10:31,480
(SOFT ORCHESTRAL
MUSIC PLAYING)

1338
01:10:31,600 --> 01:10:35,080
<i>We heard a romantic melody</i>
<i>for Princess Leia.</i>

1339
01:10:35,200 --> 01:10:38,800
We heard, uh, bellicose music
for the battle scenes.

1340
01:10:38,920 --> 01:10:42,200
